<H3> <TI>   CSCE To Send Observers to Nagorno-Karabakh </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CSCE To Send Observers to Nagorno-Karabakh </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2005124594 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 20 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU2005124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "b.b.": "Hope for Karabakh"] </F>
  [Text] Vienna -- Since the cease-fire agreed upon by the 
warring parties in the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict on 11 May has 
been holding, CSCE is now making increasing efforts to 
consolidate this truce. If the three conflicting parties 
(Azerbaijan, Armenia, Nagorno-Karabakh) sign a relevant 
agreement in Vienna, CSCE will send 34 observers to Karabakh 
within three days (10 of whom would be mine clearing experts), 
the CSCE's Karabakh rapporteur, Ambassador Jan Eliasson, told 
correspondents on Thursday [19 May]. 
  Within another two weeks, this CSCE team would be increased 
to 66. Twelve CSCE states are prepared to provide military 
personnel for the Karabakh mission. Eliasson stressed that this 
mission will be a first step toward a peace process. 
  He said that the Armenian and Azerbaijani presidents, 
Ter-Petrosyan and Aliyev, have pointed out to him that this is 
an "historic chance" to end this "war that has been forgotten by 
the world" (Eliasson). So far, cease-fires in the Karabakh 
conflict have always been broken shortly after they were signed. 
International supervisors would contribute a "new quality" to 
securing the cease-fire, Eliasson said. 

</TEXT>

