<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hesse Minister Views Ban on Deporting Kurds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hesse Minister Views Ban on Deporting Kurds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005154694 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1213 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Wiesbaden (DDP/ADN) -- Following the decision by 
Schleswig-Holstein and Rhineland-Palatinate, Hesse today decided 
on a six-month deportation ban for Kurds. After the heads of 
the state governments were unable to reach a joint solution last 
night, Hesse Interior Minister Herbert Guenther (SPD) decided in 
Wiesbaden to take this step. Kurdish offenders were to be 
excluded from the deportation ban, the Hesse Interior Ministry 
said. 
  The reason given by Guenther was that the situation of the 
Kurds in Turkey had deteriorated to such an extent that no 
responsibility could be assumed for the possible consequences of 
deportation. Guenther said the efforts of the German Government 
to make Turkey comply with human rights by means of a bilateral 
agreement were increasing doubts that deportees were at present 
dependent on the whim of government organs. Guenther called on 
the Federal Government to exert pressure on the Turkish 
Government to at last find a constructive, humanitarian solution 
to the Kurdish problem in Turkey. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

