<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Herzog Leads Presidency Vote; Second Vote Needed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Herzog Leads Presidency Vote; Second Vote Needed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305111994 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1102 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DDP/ADN) -- As expected, none of the five 
candidates for the office of federal president has achieved the 
necessary absolute majority of 663 votes in the first Federal 
Assembly ballot. Of the l,317 valid votes cast, 604 went to the 
CDU/CSU [Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union] 
candidate Roman Herzog. The SPD [Social Democratic Party] 
candidate and North Rhine-Westphalian Minister-President 
Johannes Rau received 505 votes. The FDP [Free Democratic 
Party] candidate Hildegard Hamm-Bruecher received l32 votes. 
The east German civil rights campaigner Jens Reich received 62 
votes, and the candidate of the right-wing Republicans, Hans 
Hirzel, received 12 votes. There were two abstentions, and two 
votes were invalid. 
  Thus a second ballot is required where once again an 
absolute 
majority for the election of the new federal president is 
needed. A simple majority is sufficient in a third ballot. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

