<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Clears Way for Lufthansa Privatization </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bonn Clears Way for Lufthansa Privatization </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905130294 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1155 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- Today, the cabinet approved the 
agreement between the Federal Government and Lufthansa on 
pensions for Lufthansa employees in Bonn today. The cabinet has 
thus cleared the way for a complete privatization of Lufthansa, 
Federal Transport Minister Matthias Wissmann (Christian 
Democratic Union) told the Bundestag. The privatization is a 
milestone on the path toward securing the company's 
competitiveness. 
  Agreement on the pension claims came about in early May. 
Finance Minister Waigel said he is prepared to provide 1.5 
billion marks for Lufthansa employees. As the Federal 
Government does not wish to participate in the impending 
increase in share capital, its proportion of Lufthansa shares 
will fall to under 50 percent. The agreement on a new company 
pension arrangement for the 48,000 or so Lufthansa employees was 
concluded on 10 May. 

</TEXT>

