<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Protests Delay in UN Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Protests Delay in UN Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2305115494 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2305115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Cypriot Government launched a protest today with 
the United Nations and sought explanations for the delay in the 
submission of the UN secretary general's report. Government 
Spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis stated that it is no longer 
certain that the UN secretary general's report will be 
circulated today or tomorrow, as expected. 
  The protest was made by Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis 
to Gustave Feissel, the UN secretary general's deputy special 
representative in Cyprus. The foreign minister also asked the 
UN official to explain whether Turkish press reports that the 
United Nations submitted a series of proposals to the Turkish 
Cypriot side during the deliberations in Vienna are true. The 
proposals reportedly satisfy many of the Turkish demands on 
implementing the confidence-building measures. 
  Specifically, the Turkish press reports note that the United 
Nations and Robert Lamb, the U.S. State Department special 
coordinator on Cyprus, made the following proposals to the 
Turkish side: First, two separate customs departments should be 
established; second, there should be an equal number of flights 
for the two sides from the Nicosia Airport; third, the Greek 
Cypriots' access to Famagusta will be monitored by Turkish 
Cypriot policemen in civilian clothes; and fourth, within one 
year, before the operation of the Nicosia Airport, France, 
Germany, Canada, and Australia will accept the entry of Turkish 
Cypriot citizens using Turkish Cypriot passports. The press 
reports also note that Feissel accepted that access to Famagusta 
will be controlled by the Turkish side. 
  Kasoulidhis repeated that the confidence-building measures 
process has ended, and that a Cyprus solution be promoted only 
through alternative methods. He also said that if the submission 
of the UN secretary general's report is delayed beyond Tuesday 
[24 May], it would mean that the actions of the pseudostate in 
convening the so-called council of ministers and the pseudostate 
itself receive consideration. The spokesman stressed that the 
21 March document clearly refers to all the issues. He added 
that the elements noted in the Turkish Cypriot press are new. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

