<H3> <TI>   Albania Reportedly Arrests 6 Greek-Albanians </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Albania Reportedly Arrests 6 Greek-Albanians </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Government Spokesman Comments </H4>

<F P=102> NC2005193094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1735 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2005193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Eleni Apostolopoulou] </F>
  [Text] According to information received this morning from 
a diplomatic source at the Greek Embassy in Tirana, there is 
concern about the arrest of six members of Omonoia, the Greek 
minority party in Albania, because it is not known how long they 
will be in prison. 
  The six members were charged with illegal possession of arms 
and with being associated with secret Greek groups seeking to 
change Albania's territory. The charges, which are considered 
to be equal to treason, were made against Theodhoros Bezanis, 
Iraklis Sirmos, Konstandinos Kiriakos, Evangelos Papakhristou, 
and Konstandinos Tsiavos [five names as heard]. 
  Greek minority circles believe the charges are unfounded 
because no arms other than hunting rifles were found in the 
possession of the six men. They also believe the Albanian 
Government is taking this action to create more problems in its 
relations with Greeks and to warn Omonoia what will happen if it 
publicizes its opposition to Tirana. Today's Albanian press did 
not carry any reports on the arrest of the six members, and 
there has been no official reaction so far. 
  Responding to a question on the arrest, Government Spokesman 
Evangelos Venizelos said Greece's stance toward Greek Albanians 
and the activity of the Albanian authorities is firm and well 
known. He said: We want the protection of Greeks within the 
framework of Albanian and international law. 
  Venizelos noted that the government has accepted the 
proposal 
for a meeting between the foreign ministers of the two 
countries, but added that it would be more meaningful if a 
meeting of experts was held in advance. He stressed: A top 
issue is respect for the human rights of the minority and for 
Albania to become a just state. 
  Referring to the visit by Yasushii Akashi, the UN secretary 
general's representative, to Skopje [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] and his meeting with [President 
Kiro] Gligorov, the spokesman noted that this visit must be 
evaluated along with developments in UN mediator Cyrus Vance's 
initiative. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-65748 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu099_p_94003" </HT>


