<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Albania Reportedly Arrests 6 Greek-Albanians </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Albania Reportedly Arrests 6 Greek-Albanians </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Evert Urges Diplomatic Action </H4>

<F P=102> NC2105102794 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 0900 GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2105102794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Tension has again risen in Greek-Albanian 
relations because the [Albanian President Sali] Berisha regime 
brought very serious charges against six North Epirus persons 
who are members of the Omonoia organization. Specifically, the 
Albanian authorities filed charges against six North Epirotans 
that could even result in the death penalty for so-called 
espionage, separatist acts, and contacts with the Greek 
intelligence services. [passage omitted] 
  In a statement today, New Democracy Chairman Miltiadhis 
Evert 
called on all political and social organizations to mobilize 
overseas in order to exert pressure on the Albanian Government 
to free the six Greek Albanians, who are being held 
unjustifiably and illegally. The Greek Government should deal 
with the indictment of these Greek Albanians in a strong manner 
through diplomatic avenues, Evert stressed. The opposition 
leader also stressed that the Foreign Ministry should mobilize 
all Greek ambassadors and international organizations to this 
effect. In conclusion, Evert underlined that next week New 
Democracy deputies will go to international organizations 
related to human rights to brief them and inform international 
public opinion. 

</TEXT>

