<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rwandan Official Denies UN Claims of Massacres </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rwandan Official Denies UN Claims of Massacres </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2005093894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1910 GMT 19 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2005093894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Rwanda: Tutsi Official Denies </F>
UNHCR Claims of Massacres"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Bari, Italy, May 19 -- Reports by the United 
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) of massacres and 
tortures of Rwandan refugees by armed groups belonging to the 
Rwandan Patriotic Front (FPR) were denied and labeled "totally 
unfounded" in a statement released by the Tutsi-led FPR here 
Thursday [19 May]. 
  The statement, in the form of a letter of protest to the 
UNHCR chief, Sadako Ogata, demands an "immediate and public 
retraction" of the reports, made two days ago by a UNHCR 
official in Geneva. 
  The letter was signed by Jacques Bihozagara, deputy prime 
minister of the Rwandan transition government, formed by an 
agreement in Tanzania but which never took office because of the 
outbreak of warfare between the Tutsi and the Hutu tribes. 
  "Not even our most severe critics," the FPR claims, "have 
doubted the (our) commitment to the security and dignity of all 
civilians in Rwanda." Bihozagara also called the UN agency's 
allegations "irresponsible and incomprehensible." 

</TEXT>

