<H3> <TI>   Dehaene Urges `Vigilance' Toward Italian Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dehaene Urges `Vigilance' Toward Italian Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1905120194 Brussels BELGA Database in French 1633 GMT 18 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1905120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA Database </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed ALN (ADB): "Chamber -- Neofascists in the </F>
Italian Government: Vigilance"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 18 May (BELGA) -- On Wednesday afternoon 
[18 May], the Chamber dedicated a long debate to the attitude 
which the government must take regarding the entry of the 
neofascists into the Italian Government of Silvio Berlusconi. 
It was an opportunity for Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene to 
repeat what he had already said to the same audience last 
Thursday. 
  The prime minister began by reaffirming that democracy is 
like a fragile plant. "So it requires constant vigilance and an 
effort on the part of each individual." Jean-Luc Dehaene also 
reiterated that Italy is a democratic country. "The elections 
took place there in full respect of the constitutional rules. 
Consequently, the results must be accepted," he said, adding 
that "the Italian Government had been formed in a legally 
correct manner." 
  "Within the European Union," he went on, "Belgium will 
reaffirm the democratic principles and continue to be highly 
vigilant in ensuring that they are respected. Regarding direct 
bilateral contacts with foreign colleagues, it is up to each 
individual Belgian minister to decide on and regulate them 
personally, naturally within the context of Belgian European 
policy," the prime minister concluded. He was applauded by the 
entire majority, including the PS [Walloon Socialist Party], 
whose bureau had asked last Monday that the government adopt a 
clear position. 
  At the end of the debate, the four majority parties tabled a 
motion pure and simple. 

</TEXT>

