  [Excerpt] Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos today 
reiterated Athens' firm decision to insist that the human rights 
of the Greek minority in Albania be respected in order to 
improve relations with Tirana. Venizelos reminded the Albanian 
Government about the recent demarches that Greece made to 
international organizations about the issue. 
  The spokesman made this statement after [Albanian President 
Sali] Berisha's regime accused six individuals from North 
Ipirotes of serious charges following the border incident in 
Episkopi. Venizelos stressed that the Greek Government has 
always linked the improvement of Greek-Albanian relations, an 
improvement that it wants and pursues, to full respect for the 
Greek Albanian's human rights. He added that Greek-Albanian 
relations as well as Albania's relations with the European Union 
[EU] depend on this prerequisite. 
  Venizelos concluded: Greece will lodge new diplomatic 
demarches with all the international organizations and third 
countries. It has already lodged demarches with the United 
Nations, CSCE, the EU, and the U.S. Government. [passage 
omitted] 

