<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Attack On PKK Camp Kills 9, Injures 1,000 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Attack On PKK Camp Kills 9, Injures 1,000 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2005192194 Istanbul HURRIYET in Turkish 20 May 94 p 14 </F>
<F P=103> NC2005192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Istanbul HURRIYET </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Umit Sezgin report: "Nine Militants Killed, 1,000 Others </F>
Wounded in Zalakh Camp"] 
  [Text] Al-Sulaymaniyah--BIRAYATI [as published], the organ 
of the Democratic Party of Kurdistan, reported yesterday that 
nine militants from the Workers Party of Kurdistan [PKK] were 
killed and 1,000 others injured when several Turkish military 
aircraft attacked the PKK camp in Zalakh two days ago. 
Meanwhile, the PKK, which recently established close relations 
with Jalal Talabani, leader of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan 
[PUK], has issued a statement on the attack through that party. 
The PUK official in Irbil said that Kala Dizeh, commander of 
the Zalakh camp, informed his office that "the attack by the 
Turkish military planes was completely unsuccessful. No one was 
killed or wounded." 
  The air attack on the camp created a shock wave in northern 
Iraq. Many of the PKK militants, who did not expect another 
attack after the air raid in February, had already returned to 
the camp. With the return of the militants, the military 
officials in Turkey ordered several F-4 and F-104 aircraft to 
take off from their bases in Malatya and Diyarbakir to attack 
the camp for the second time. It has been reported that all the 
buildings and other constructions in the camp were destroyed. 
Meanwhile, it has been learned that groups of PKK militants 
have begun to leave the vicinity of the camp. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-65759 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu099_q_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

