<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials React To Herzog Victory, Speech </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials React To Herzog Victory, Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kinkel Rejects SPD Criticism </H4>

<F P=102> LD2405124294 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1149 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405124294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DDP/ADN) -- In the view of FDP [Free 
Democratic Party] Chairman Klaus Kinkel, the decision by the 
liberals to support new Federal President Roman Herzog is 
important for the strategic orientation of the FDP in the 1994 
election year. The liberals have proved themselves to be a 
reliable factor, Kinkel said following a group meeting of his 
party in the Berlin Reichstag today. The FDP acted responsibly 
in its key role in the election of the federal president. 
  The SPD [Social Democratic Party] candidate, Rau, enjoyed 
his 
high regard, Kinkel continued. At the same time, he strongly 
criticized SPD comments suggesting the FDP was no longer needed. 
"I do not like aggressive noises of this kind; we will not let 
ourselves be blackmailed by the SPD." The FDP was free to 
decide for whom it wanted to vote. 
  Asked to comment on the discussion about a direct election 
of 
the head of state, Kinkel said this could be discussed. 
However, it had to be considered whether this should also apply 
to other representatives. Kinkel admitted that he was 
personally opposed to direct election by the people. 
  Asked whether the FDP has a favorite candidate for the new 
president of the Federal Constitutional Court, Kinkel said he 
did not wish to comment but already has a favorite. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

