<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Report on CBM's Postponed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Report on CBM's Postponed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2405071394 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0430 GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2405071394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] There are unclear reports from New York about the 
postponement of the UN secretary general's report to the 
Security Council. Last night, UN alternate spokesman 'Ahmad 
Fawzi said the report would be submitted by the end of the week 
and clarified that the international organization has no 
information that Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas has 
accepted the confidence-building measures [CBM's]. 
  But the Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation correspondent in New 
York reported that according to UN Security Council circles, 
after intervention by Turkish diplomats, the Turkish side has 
been given a new extension until the end of May. According to 
the same information, Inal Batu, the Turkish permanent 
representative to the United Nations, sought a meeting with 
Marrack Goulding, Alternate UN Secretary General, at which time 
he conveyed a Turkish Government request that the report not be 
submitted before 31 May. His justification was that the Turkish 
Cypriot community is still holding meetings with Gustave 
Feissel, the UN secretary general's alternate special 
representative in Cyprus. The Turkish representative also 
claimed that Denktas informed Ankara of his decision to accept 
the 21 March UN document on the CBM's but said he could not 
announce it to Feissel before the extraordinary meetings of the 
pseudogovernment and the pseudoparliament today and tomorrow 
respectively. 
  According to our correspondent, UN Security Council circles 
said the Turkish side was given the requested extension after it 
was stressed that no new extension would be given. U.S. 
officials said an extension would not be given even for the 
so-called referendum that Denktas may attempt to hold. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-65825 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu100_h_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-100 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel, Ruehe: No Medical Troops to Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel, Ruehe: No Medical Troops to Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2005163794 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 20 May 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU2005163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["eli/ub"-signed report: "Bonn: No Medical Troops to </F>
Rwanda"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel (Free 
Democratic Party of Germany) has joined Volker Ruehe (Christian 
Democratic Union) in his decision not to send German medical 
troops to civil war-stricken Rwanda for the time being. Ruehe 
had said: "We will not send our troops to Rwanda." The Foreign 
Ministry said that if the defense minister, who is the minister 
responsible for such missions, finds that the use of German 
troops is out of the question, the foreign minister can only 
agree to that view. 
  A week ago, the United Nations had asked Bonn via the German 
Mission in New York whether it would be prepared to send a 
medical unit of 100 soldiers, a field hospital, and 50 vehicles, 
as well as an air transport unit to Rwanda. In a paper 
assessing the matter, the Foreign Office says that this was a 
"deviation from general practice." Usually, such requests are 
made orally and on all the members of the community. In the 
case of Rwanda, Germany was approached direct and in writing. 
This shows the urgency with which the matter is being treated 
and the pressure that the Security Council is putting behind the 
request. 
  Irrespective of this request, a Bundeswehr Transall aircraft 
is to take drugs and food to Rwanda. Government spokesman 
Dieter Vogel said that the cabinet is "clearly willing" to meet 
a relevant request by UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali. But 
first it must be clarified whether the situation is secure 
enough for such a mission. The Transall plane is to operate as a 
shuttle taking drugs and food from Nairobi to the Rwandan 
capital Kigali. 
  The request from New York for the deployment of medical 
troops has not yet been officially decided in Bonn. Ruehe said 
that the security situation in Rwanda has to be clarified first 
and the conflicting parties must agree to the mission. Also, 
irritations must be avoided prior to the Federal Constitutional 
Court passing its judgment on international Bundeswehr missions. 
  The Foreign Ministry said that there is absolute chaos in 
Rwanda. The security of German medical troops would not be 
safeguarded. Kinkel is torn between two opinions in the Rwanda 
question. On the one hand he said that Germany must not stand 
aside when there is a genocide happening. On the other hand, he 
said that no European country is currently prepared to send 
troops to the African country. 
  Kinkel and Ruehe had already discussed the UN request on 
Wednesday [18 May]. In this discussion, Kinkel was especially 
responsive to the argument of danger to German troops. The 
decision to provide the Transall was made in a talk between 
Kinkel, Ruehe, and Friedrich Bohl, the minister in the 
Chancellor's Office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

