<H3> <TI>   SPD Politicians Criticize Herzog Acceptance Speech </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPD Politicians Criticize Herzog Acceptance Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2305185794 Hamburg DPA in German 1728 GMT 23 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2305185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Berlin (DPA) -- Leading Social Democratic Party 
of Germany [SPD] politicians have reacted with harsh criticism 
to the acceptance speech of future President Roman Herzog at the 
Federal Convention in Berlin. "The best thing one can do is not 
to comment on the speech," SPD Chairman Rudolf Scharping said on 
Monday evening [23 May]. Deputy SPD Chairman Wolfgang Thierse 
stated that Herzog immediately lived up to his reputation as an 
arch-conservative and terrified half of those present. Peter 
Struck, parliamentary manager of the SPD group, called the 
speech "disastrous." 
  SPD Deputy Chairman Oskar Lafontaine said that Herzog 
probably did not prepare his speech well. Therefore, one should 
not weigh his every word. Reinhard Hoeppner, SPD land chairman 
of Saxony-Anhalt, was "relatively shocked" by the speech. 
  Joschka Fischer, Hesse environment minister and Greens top 
politician, shook his head and said: "Read the speech; this 
says more than any comment." Former FRG Interior Minister 
Gerhart Baum stated: "My skepticism regarding the newly elected 
president has not declined after this speech." 
  On the other hand, Christian Democratic Union/Christian 
Social Union [CDU/CSU] Group Chairman Wolfgang Schaeuble said 
that Herzog's election is a "good day for Germany." The elected 
head of state is a man who has always felt committed to German 
unification. CSU Land Group Chairman Michael Glos expressed the 
conviction that Herzog will be a good president. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

