<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scharping: Herzog Selection `Demonstration of Power' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Scharping: Herzog Selection `Demonstration of Power' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2405110494 Hamburg DPA in German 0934 GMT 24 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2405110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DPA) -- The Social Democratic Party [SPD] 
has reacted to the election of the new federal president, Roman 
Herzog, by sharply criticizing Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl 
and the Free Democratic Party [FDP]. SPD Chairman Rudolf 
Scharping told journalists in Berlin on 24 May that the Bonn 
coalition had only had an interest in "demonstrating power" in 
this connection. 
  The selection of the Christian Democratic Union/Christian 
Social Union [CDU/CSU] candidate was not marked by the will to 
find the best president for the Germans, "but by Helmut Kohl's 
power policy calculation." He said the SPD was in agreement 
with most Germans that Johannes Rau would have been the better 
choice. 
  The SPD chairman said the SPD would cooperate loyally with 
the new head of state. However, the Social Democrats expected 
Herzog to conduct his office "in an absolutely impartial way" 
and to orient himself at the line pursued by his predecessor, 
Richard von Weizsaecker. His first official speech on Monday 
evening [23 May] had, however, failed to create this impression, 
said Scharping. 
  The SPD chief also sharply criticized the FDP. By their 
attitude in the Federal Convention, they had abandoned their 
role as an independent political force. What they presented as 
loyalty to the coalition, was complete subjugation, said 
Scharping. It was typical for FDP Chairman Klaus Kinkel to 
virtually have to ask for a vote of confidence, in order to push 
through his line. 
  Despite his defeat, Johannes Rau had met with broad support 
in the Federal Convention and above all from the people. The 
SPD would make use of this impetus for the upcoming elections 
and would make the European elections in three weeks a "fourth 
ballot," said Scharping. 

</TEXT>

