<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: Public Favors Joint Intervention in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll: Public Favors Joint Intervention in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2405124394 Paris AFP in English 1151 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2405124394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, May 24 (AFP) -- Some 68 percent of French 
people would favour French military intervention on behalf of 
Bosnia's Moslem-led government, but only in the framework of a 
joint U.S.-European operation, an opinion poll revealed Tuesday 
[24 May]. 
  Were France to take such an initiative on its own, 77 
percent 
of people would oppose it, according to a survey by the polling 
institute IFOP for publication in Wednesday's Globe-Hebdo 
magazine. 
  In all, 29 percent of 974 people questioned in the telephone 
poll said they opposed French intervention even as part of a 
joint operation. 
  If "the Europeans and Americans refused" to intervene in the 
conflict, 20 percent of those questioned said they would favour 
action by France alone. 
  A "solidarity train" was meanwhile to leave Paris for Zagreb 
stacked with packages for refugee camps in former Yugoslavia, in 
an initiative by the French humanitarian association 
Europa/l'Odyssee, reports said. 
  The Paris-Zagreb solidarity train, an idea backed by the 
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural 
Organisation, will leave Paris on June 18 and make stops in 
Geneva and Milan before arriving in Zagreb the following day. 
  During the journey, doctors, psychiatrists and humanitarian 
officials will debate the trauma of war and the "art of living 
in peace," organizers said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-65882 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu101_i_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-101 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Elections: Poll Shows 3.5-Point Drop for Majority </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Elections: Poll Shows 3.5-Point Drop for Majority </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2405143494 Paris LE FIGARO in French 23 May 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BR2405143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE FIGARO </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "European Election Opinion Poll: </F>
Baudis at 32 Percent, Rocard at 19 Percent"] 
  [Text] According to a Louis Harris poll commissioned by LE 
JOURNAL DE DIMANCHE, the UDF-RPR [French Democratic Union-Rally 
for the Republic] election list headed by Dominique Baudis would 
win 32 percent of votes cast, down by 3.5 points. In the 
previous Louis Harris poll, Dominique Baudis' list had been 
given 35.5 percent of voting intentions. Michel Rocard's 
Socialist list has risen two points to 19 percent (from 17 
percent). Bernard Tapie's MRG [Movement of the Radical Left] 
has risen one point to 10 percent (from 9 percent), while 
Jean-Marie Le Pen's National Front has risen one-half point to 
also stand at 10 percent. Next come Philippe de Villiers' 
"Other Europe" list and the PCF [French Communist Party] list of 
Francois Wurtz with 7 percent. They are followed by [former 
Defense Minister] Jean-Pierre Chevenement's "Alternative Policy" 
list, whose score remains unchanged at 4.5 percent. Brice 
Lalonde's Ecology Generation list also remains stable at 3.5 
percent, ahead of its ecologist rival, the Greens, led by 
Marie-Ann Isler-Beguin, which is down two points from 4 to 2 
percent. This poll was carried out by telephone on 19 May using 
a national sample of 1,013 people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

