<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Take-It-or-Leave-It' Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Take-It-or-Leave-It' Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2605115994 Paris AFP in English 1048 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2605115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Talloires, France, May 26 (AFP) -- International 
negotiators were considering presenting a take-it-or-leave-it 
peace plan Thursday [26 May] to Bosnia's belligerents, who are 
balking at European proposals to carve-up the country, a 
diplomat close to the talks said. 
  The diplomat said the "contact group" of European, UN, U.S. 
and Russian negotiators were ready to try to impose a 
territorial solution on the warring parties, presumably by 
threatening to withdraw peacekeeping forces from Bosnia if the 
new plan was rejected. 
  The diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 
closed-door negotiations which began at this French Alpine 
resort on Wednesday between the contact group and Bosnia's 
Croats, Moslems and Serbs "did not bring any new elements" 
despite earlier reports of progress. 
  "Each party is sticking to their earlier position, whereby 
the idea of considering a more authoritarian approach," the 
source said. 
  He said Wednesday's talks focussed exclusively on 
constitutional issues and the territorial carve-up of Bosnia. 
  "There was no mention of the fighting," he said. 
  The contact group held separate talks with each of the 
Bosnian delegations representing the country's Moslems, Croats 
and Serbs, the source added. 
  There have been no official comments on progress, but a 
member of the Croat press contingent who said he had access to 
the meeting reported Wednesday that the Croats and Moslems, who 
have agreed to form a federation, had dropped demands for more 
territory. 
  He said they had agreed to negotiate on the basis of a 
European Union plan backed by the contact group which would 
allot 51 percent of Bosnian territory to the Moslem-Croat 
federation and 49 percent to the Serbs. 
  The Moslems and Croats now control 30 percent of the 
republic's territory and were demanding 58 percent -- 
corresponding to the areas which had Croat and Moslem majorities 
before the two-year-old war. Bosnian Serbs control the 
remaining 70 percent of the territory. 
  France and Britain, the main providers of troops for the UN 
peacekeeping operation, have warned they might pull their 
soldiers out of Bosnia by the end of the year if no serious 
progress is made towards restoring peace. 
  The talks here were to wind up Thursday and are expected to 
resume in about 10 days at a location not yet announced to 
prepare a conference of foreign ministers around mid-June as a 
follow-up to one in Geneva on May 13. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

