<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> The Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Slow Growth Predicted Until 1998 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Slow Growth Predicted Until 1998 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2505150194 Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD in Dutch 25 May 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> BR2505150194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Slow Growth for Netherlands </F>
Economy"] 
  [Text] The growth of the Netherlands economy in the next 
few years looks set to be just above the European average, while 
Europe as a whole is going to lag behind Japan and the United 
States. These forecasts are made in the report entitled "Europe 
in 1998," published today by the Netherlands Economic Institute 
in Rotterdam. 
  The Netherlands economy will grow by 1.9 percent until 1998, 
while the European Union (EU) average will grow by 1.8 percent, 
the institute predicts. The recovery of the European economy 
thus looks set to be far from vigorous and will certainly not be 
enough to solve the unemployment problem. After 1996, growth is 
even set to fall off again, according to the institute's 
computing models. During the period 1992-1998, the United States 
and Japan should experience a 2.6 percent growth. 
  Europe must come to terms with the fact that most growth is 
going to come from Asia and the developing countries, the 
researchers write. These countries are set to experience growth 
of 6.9 percent and 4 percent, respectively, over the same 
period. The report states that it will not be enough to count 
on technological innovation alone. New products must also be 
linked to new forms of services, and at low prices. Europe must 
develop new mass consumer goods. Education, technology and, 
most importantly, the transfer of technical know-how must all be 
stimulated. As in the NAFTA countries (United States, Canada 
and the developing country Mexico), benefit must be drawn from 
the low labor costs in East Europe by closely involving the East 
European countries in the EU. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

