<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Loses Popularity Lead Over Kohl </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Loses Popularity Lead Over Kohl </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605102794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0824 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605102794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cologne (DDP/ADN) --The SPD [Social Democratic Party 
of Germany] and its candidate for chancellor, Rudolf Scharping, 
have lost their lead in popularity over Chancellor Helmut Kohl 
and the CDU/CSU [Christian Democratic Union/Christian Socialist 
Union] five months before the Bundestag elections. This is the 
result of a survey carried out by the Forsa Institute for the 
"RTL- Kanzlerbarometer" program which the RTL TV channel 
published today. According to the survey, Scharping and Kohl are 
neck and neck in popularity among the voters, both at 32 
percent. Thirty-nine percent of Germans would vote CDU/CSU [if 
there were an election] this week, 40 percent would vote SPD, 8 
percent Alliance 90/Greens, 6 percent FDP [Free Democratic 
Party] and 3 percent for both the PDS [Party of Democratic 
Socialism] and the Republicans. 
  Twenty percent of Germans believe that the Union [CDU/CSU] 
is 
the best suited to solve the country's problems. Only 14 
percent have confidence in the SPD in this respect. The 
majority of Germans (62 percent), however, believe that no party 
is in a position to do so. 

</TEXT>

