<H3> <TI>   Jutta Limbach New Constitutional Court President </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jutta Limbach New Constitutional Court President </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505163094 Berlin DIE WELT in German 25 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2505163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Welt-Nachrichtendienst" report: "Jutta Limbach (SPD) To </F>
Succeed Herzog"] 
  [Text] Berlin -- Former Berlin Justice Senator Jutta 
Limbach, Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD], is to succeed 
Roman Herzog, Christian Democratic Union [CDU], and become the 
first female president of the Federal Constitutional Court in 
Karlsruhe. Mrs. Limbach has been chairwoman of the Second Panel 
and vice president since March upon the proposal of the SPD. 
  One day after Herzog's election as the new president, 
Wolfgang Schaeuble, chairman of the CDU/Christian Social Union 
[CSU] Bundestag group, stated in Berlin yesterday that it is a 
"tested tradition" that the highest-ranking post of the supreme 
German court is alternated among the parties. 
  The CDU then has the right to suggest a new constitutional 
judge to replace Herzog. In Bonn, jurist and former FRG Defense 
Minister Rupert Scholz was named as a potential candidate. 

</TEXT>

